Environmental-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUXELLES – In Brussels as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
This time, however, it's about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest carbon market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
But these measures, important though they are, are not sufficient to meet today's challenges.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
We still have reasons to remain optimistic.
Look at these people, growing in numbers day by day, ready to act to challenge their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also committing, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the politicians and policymakers, at both national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Seize it!
And make a green Europe our top political priority for the years ahead, focused on three fronts.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no choice but to reduce net EU carbon dioxide emissions to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest heavily in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transportation, as well as commercial maritime and air transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a true circular economy that minimizes waste.
Every year, 8 billion tons of materials are transformed into energy or products within the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tons come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require focusing on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let us get started today by launching, for example, a European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronics, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to WWF, wild species populations have declined by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The UN conference on biodiversity, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We need to strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We also need to launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to accompany this green transition.
But these colossal tasks that lie ahead of us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same – and the most vulnerable – who bear the costs.
All measures considered must therefore first and foremost be designed to minimize social costs.
And at the same time, we must work today with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
For it is pointless to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three areas could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the new political cycle of the EU.
Because we are in an acute ecological debt, and it would be more than justified that the stability and growth pact applied to member states' public finances finds an equivalent for green Europe objectives!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action across all sectors: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not fear using its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of eco-design legislation and extended producer responsibility for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in annual investments to meet its Paris Agreement commitments.
This is a feasible goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
And the new EU budget and investment plan, leveraging private sector investments, could further enhance the Union's ability to act on environmental and climate issues.
The financial sector will need to play a fundamental role: through climate-related financial disclosures, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway’s sovereign wealth fund and BlackRock, to adopt a longer-term perspective and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, while some member states may see this as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, as well as subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, integrating sustainability into public spending.
Behind these initiatives, the key lies in the approach. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must define ambitious goals and short- and long-term 'missions' that resonate socially.
With member states and the European Parliament, we will need to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be achieved overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to avoid facing the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a European Green New Deal. But it is not too late.
Let us not miss this new opportunity!
